<div id="review_469280675" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/469280675" />
    <a title="Deb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5276322-deb"><img alt="Deb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642833537p2/5276322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/469280675?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deb" href="/user/show/5276322-deb">Deb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer469280675" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9631062756292151838"><b>
  <i>Glad to finish.</i>
</b><br/><br/>I am so sorry to those who have read and loved this book but I did not because it is flat. I really wanted to like this book but I just don&apos;t feel I was brought into any serious connection with these characters at all. The only picture I have of them is from the movie and that in my opinion is not good. Having read several books that have been adapted for movies I just believe the book should have more detail after all it&apos;s words but no, not with this one. Don&apos;t get me wrong, </span>
  <span id="freeText9631062756292151838" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>Glad to finish.</i>
</b><br /><br />I am so sorry to those who have read and loved this book but I did not because it is flat. I really wanted to like this book but I just don't feel I was brought into any serious connection with these characters at all. The only picture I have of them is from the movie and that in my opinion is not good. Having read several books that have been adapted for movies I just believe the book should have more detail after all it's words but no, not with this one. Don't get me wrong, there were words and adjectives per se but just functionally. I jumped into this book next because after reading my last phenomenal book choice, I was in the mood to read a little romance but this was a disappointed. No flowery beauty, passion or anything that made me feel a single emotion. I became bored frequently and found myself pushing, which I hate. Everything was so "blah". Even the supposed love affair was just "blah, really, your in love after two days, without a stitch of passion or anything remotely romantical..oh ok whatever, are we finished yet?" I started skimming, A LOT. I felt also that it was evident that this was written by a man because there were supposed attempts at describing her attraction to him that were just..not what we would think at all. I felt like the author was trying too hard to write what he thought a woman would want to hear but it was sad and unconvincing. It's like it was written by some 90 year old great grandpa who said "In my day we had nice stories to listen to around the fire.." And we all sat around bored to tears as grandpa Sparks told us a tale. About entertaining as an old boot. Ho hum, think I'll stick with the movie on this one and I don't even think it's one of my favorites. Oh well, I'm sure considering the material the director did his best with the movie.<br /><br />Two stars any rating system. Do I recommend? Eh...(shrugs). <br />Next!!!!<br />The book challenge continues. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9631062756292151838" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


